1. Start with a graded k-algebra R = ⨁ d, R_d.
2. Assume G acts on R by k-algebra automorphisms.
3. Define the invariant subalgebra R^G.
4. Assume the action preserves grading: g(R_d) ⊆ R_d.
5. Show each homogeneous component of an invariant element is still invariant.
6. Define the degree-d piece of R^G by
      (R^G)_d := R_d ∩ R^G.
7. Conclude that
      R^G = ⨁ d, (R^G)_d,
   so R^G is a graded k-subalgebra of R.
